1163E297AB8142F39E25D97FB0CA6DD4.description:
Untrustworthy (often free) downloads from
freeware or shareware sites can contain
malware.

379400CEB0E44683A403C74C626769DC.description:
Unsolicited emails, attachments, links, and
forms in emails can be used to compromise
the security of a computing system. These
can come from unknown senders or from
known senders whose security has been
compromised.

A4A8C47BD85245CF8BD23F6BBDC6D091.description:
A malicious link can be disguised on a web
page or in an email message.

38D6BA58A9614956AE303FAA16663140.description:
A rogue access point is a wireless access
pointthatgivesunauthorizedaccesstosecure
networks.

B851A8F37FFA44599B70DFAFE7CF5F84.description:
Data sent over public networks can be
intercepted,analyzed,andmodified.Oneway
that this can happen is through a rogue access
point.

6D322078F84C44B3B4A7ED820D721E1E.description:
Keylogging is the use of a program to record
every keystroke made by a computer user in
order to gain fraudulent access to passwords
andotherconfidentialinformation.

D7CCE2B9E52C4037AC917A83C45B9390.description:
Phishing is a technique that attempts to trick
a user into providing personal information.
That personal information can then be used
to access sensitive online resources, such as
bank accounts and emails.

C6D423E05C05428A8F9317A00B218081.description:
Explainhowunauthorized
access to computing
resources is gained.

B609CE992A174738992D3BF8A5FC3068.description:
Users can control the permissions programs
have for collecting user information. Users
should review the permission settings of
programs to protect their privacy.

730ADE004FFB4F1FAE0CB2878F0E0C21.description:
Allreal-worldsystemshaveerrorsordesign
flawsthatcanbeexploitedtocompromise
them.Regularsoftwareupdateshelpfixerrors
that could compromise a computing system.

78358B2776B642898E2010EC2259DE51.description:
Malware is software intended to damage a
computing system or to take partial control
over its operation.

2FD8772DAD2844D997075464DCD4A467.description:
A computer virus is a malicious program that
can copy itself and gain access to a computer
inanunauthorizedway.Computervirusesoften
attach themselves to legitimate programs and
start running independently on a computer.

BB3DCBEEF7A94954A82F8FEA725E810B.description:
Computer virus and malware scanning
software can help protect a computing system
against infection.

848533BE31E848C69D04C1112C385CA1.description:
Certificateauthoritiesissuedigitalcertificates
that validate the ownership of encryption keys
used in secure communications and are based
on a trust model.

42B6792E1432412880469D434B2DDCE9.description:
Encryption is the process of encoding data to
preventunauthorizedaccess.Decryption is the
process of decoding the data. Two common
encryption approaches are:
§ Symmetric key encryption involves one key
for both encryption and decryption.
§ Public key encryption pairs a public key for
encryption and a private key for decryption.
The sender does not need the receiver’s
private key to encrypt a message, but the
receiver’s private key is required to decrypt
the message.

FD5591ACBC9E42C6A8C6D070A93D2101.description:
Multifactor authentication requires at least two
steps to unlock protected information; each
step adds a new layer of security that must be
brokentogainunauthorizedaccess.

12BE958740BD4B91BEEF7DE9DA71329B.description:
Multifactor authentication is a method of
computer access control in which a user is only
granted access after successfully presenting
several separate pieces of evidence to an
authentication mechanism, typically in at least
two of the following categories: knowledge
(something they know), possession (something
they have), and inherence (something they are).

28AF83F21C6E459D9A60513812059B92.description:
A strong password is something that is easy for
ausertorememberbutwouldbedifficultfor
someone else to guess based on knowledge of
that user.

E4AD83926F8B4D278E7B5B878CFB0B4E.description:
Authentication measures protect devices
andinformationfromunauthorizedaccess.
Examples of authentication measures
include strong passwords and multifactor
authentication.

1851752B4B9D489992977AD864A20D06.description:
Explain how computing
resources can be protected
and can be misused.

B0078E736F254287AA34849339D4E498.description:
Information posted to social media services
can be used by others. Combining information
posted on social media and other sources
can be used to deduce private information
about you.

A3BE2E4EDB824D76926D40C261B3C7EC.description:
Programs can collect your location and record
where you have been, how you got there, and
how long you were at a given location.

C47E0009B3C24FF896EF1D67D18EC434.description:
PII can be used to stalk or steal the identity
of a person or to aid in the planning of other
criminal acts.

0FE3639C391740B6A84B7A37FFEAD6BD.description:
Information placed online can be used in ways
that were not intended and that may have a
harmful impact. For example, an email message
may be forwarded, tweets can be retweeted,
and social media posts can be viewed by
potential employers.

84A97521AA124FCBAE4ABF4C85E7FB64.description:
Commercial and governmental curation of
information may be exploited if privacy and
other protections are ignored.

819346FBC49A4BC48E7646E74DF7847E.description:
PII stored online can be used to simplify making
online purchases.

13B85617065046B681BF588BBCC95F50.description:
PII and other information placed online can be
used to enhance a user’s online experiences.

CD66D22B81BF40B7951FC8B40A74F1B8.description:
Disparate personal data, such as geolocation,
cookies, and browsing history, can be
aggregated to create knowledge about an
individual.

94D66AADCD274B03BDBADD0C5FE8B99F.description:
Search engines can use search history to
suggest websites or for targeted marketing.

23B2AC83693A4A1DADDC70E0888EA3BD.description:
Technology enables the collection, use, and
exploitation of information about, by, and for
individuals, groups, and institutions.

1D197FEB76BF48F2BCF716F15D5C4A45.description:
Devices, websites, and networks can collect
information about a user’s location.

97B056F6572A4DBE924292F3EF4B9582.description:
Websites can record and maintain a history of
individuals who have viewed their pages.

2D824AFC6CDC41A1B477CB9B3D42895A.description:
Search engines can record and maintain a
history of searches made by users.

728F6B551BE7439985C761B5A63F7930.description:
Personallyidentifiableinformation(PII)is
informationaboutanindividualthatidentifies,
links, relates, or describes them. Examples of
PII include:
§ Social Security number
§
§
§ phone number(s)
§ medical information
§
§ biometric data

BC922D9A7235419DAC22493CFBE0F827.description:
Describe the risks to privacy
from collecting and storing
personal data on a computer
system.

42A6F44222E9455387B0AAA454D72188.description: The use of computing innovations may involve risks to personal safety and identity.

B33385C2B0974CA08A7A13989BF39037.description:
Computing innovations can raise legal and
ethical concerns. Some examples of these
include:
§ the development of software that allows
access to digital media downloads and
streaming
§ the development of algorithms that include
bias

822FAA2FA79542DD97826CC57A9C6BE1.description:
The digital divide raises ethical concerns
around computing.

880FA84B0FD34E3A8203854E40BA4EA4.description:
Computing can play a role in social and political
issues, which in turn often raises legal and
ethical concerns.

B38E5077B1544A229E5BB2B3C4891CF6.description:
As with any technology or medium, using
computing to harm individuals or groups of
people raises legal and ethical concerns.

9917BC6ADD9341A2850E433F0BB67464.description:
Creative Commons, open source, and open
access have enabled broad access to digital
information.

A72244D3F5C540EA903987D16DEFA589.description:
The use of material created by someone other
than you should always be cited.

3C58DC09DB014EA8A2FF4116549F5945.description:
Some examples of legal ways to use materials
created by someone else include:
§ CreativeCommons—apubliccopyright
license that enables the free distribution
of an otherwise copyrighted work. This is
used when the content creator wants to give
others the right to share, use, and build upon
the work they have created.
§ opensource—programsthataremade
freely available and may be redistributed and
modified
§ openaccess—onlineresearchoutputfreeof
any and all restrictions on access and free of
many restrictions on use, such as copyright
or license restrictions

29DEA20685A446E5ACDEAD293B08C353.description:
The use of material created by someone
else without permission and presented as
one’s own is plagiarism and may have legal
consequences.

F4C52E5031DC4FE5ACE178FE4B5A69D1.description:
Measures should be taken to safeguard
intellectual property.

7100744CA097463BA666106C1E6CCDF0.description:
Easeofaccessanddistributionofdigitized
information raises intellectual property
concerns regarding ownership, value, and use.

4984A651AB694A10A56446D68BE38DE3.description:
Material created on a computer is the
intellectual property of the creator or an
organization.

A99CA9235A9344C2B99DC173338E73D1.description:
Explain how the use of
computing can raise legal
and ethical concerns.

95C0C17013814DBD8DFC70AF6D41FCB7.description:
Crowdsourcingoffersnewmodelsfor
collaboration, such as connecting businesses
or social causes with funding.

2D8E9473FE814B469ADFE40429A42E48.description:
Human capabilities can be enhanced by
collaboration via computing.

9CB7242458974B0F9995FDE3DB91DD1B.description:
Crowdsourcing is the practice of obtaining
input or information from a large number of
people via the Internet.

8DFA7B3A46804CEE8B9059623B6C311C.description:
Citizenscienceisscientificresearch
conducted in whole or part by distributed
individuals, many of whom may not be
scientists, who contribute relevant data to
research using their own computing devices.

58D5560F3B254D5286D2056585760994.description:
Widespread access to information and public
datafacilitatestheidentificationofproblems,
development of solutions, and dissemination
of results.

77871A46AAE1454EBE42F4C032EACC41.description:
Explain how people participate
inproblem-solvingprocesses
at scale.

6D86EF20A32444708A5A0FEBA6322A4F.description:
Biases can be embedded at all levels of
software development.

06106EBB7859468193AAAC90F04246BB.description:
Programmers should take action to reduce bias
in algorithms used for computing innovations
as a way of combating existing human biases.

2C981CD4A3E345A38D31794192CAE53F.description:
Computinginnovationscanreflectexisting
human biases because of biases written into
the algorithms or biases in the data used by the
innovation.

5B1AA77F4F644444BE6D04829BA3FEBF.description:
Explain how bias exists in
computing innovations.

7F4F92C6F43F4500AA58F8A19C4B765E.description:
The digital divide raises issues of equity,
access,andinfluence,bothgloballyandlocally.

C5BEE0F8320E4EA1AB69FE92F2145958.description:
The“digitaldivide”referstodifferingaccessto
computing devices and the Internet, based on
socioeconomic, geographic, or demographic
characteristics.

61B2006F0B764FD6B7FEFEE18720A3FF.description:
Internet access varies between
socioeconomic, geographic, and demographic
characteristics, as well as between countries.

B25F7A3C680746A2BE4CE7CFCFFA8FF3.description:
Describe issues that
contribute to the digital divide.

C86537653C9A4F20BDD90364B1F67A28.description:
Rapid sharing of a program or running a
program with a large number of users can result
insignificantimpactsbeyondtheintended
purpose or control of the programmer.

052E44E75B554DA6A517208D34C644B8.description:
Computing innovations have often had
unintendedbeneficialeffectsbyleadingto
advancesinotherfields.

F5BADB379A2F42B38865D94582C97D1A.description:
It is not possible for a programmer to consider
all the ways a computing innovation can be
used.

7FC3AA681ECD441993B955CD3CCF3D37.description:
Responsible programmers try to consider the
unintended ways their computing innovations
canbeusedandthepotentialbeneficialand
harmfuleffectsofthesenewuses.

E616F29519674C58AD5B5D759AA40D89.description:
Some of the ways computing innovations can
be used may have a harmful impact on society,
the economy, or culture.

93720888D8CE49B79BCCCA1EE8AB8A2B.description:
Computing innovations can be used in ways
that their creators had not originally intended:

§
§ Targeted advertising is used to help
businesses, but it can be misused at both
individual and aggregate levels.
§ Machine learning and data mining have
enabled innovation in medicine, business,
and science, but information discovered in
this way has also been used to discriminate
against groups of individuals.

47AD08D89A5F4453BC4441E60D6550CB.description:
Explain how a computing
innovation can have an impact
beyond its intended purpose.

60CD6F76BB7D4EE8951A0CB435E6A188.description:
Advances in computing have generated and
increasedcreativityinotherfields,suchas
medicine, engineering, communications, and
the arts.

D141733246524AC288F1889705401984.description:
The way people complete tasks often changes
to incorporate new computing innovations.

D8AD65561E524A42847C0E09285A92F2.description:
Explainhowaneffectofa
computing innovation can be
bothbeneficialandharmful.

A683E395101249C4ABD993F7B7114579.description:
When increasing the use of parallel computing
inasolution,theefficiencyofthesolution
is still limited by the sequential portion. This
means that at some point, adding parallel
portions will no longer meaningfully increase
efficiency

60CE2BEB38B642EFBD016C2A73BA0A97.description:
Distributed computing allows much larger
problems to be solved quicker than they could
be solved using a single computer.

BBD787109DE34D57A05AF52E202432A4.description:
Distributed computing allows problems to be
solved that could not be solved on a single
computer because of either the processing
time or storage needs involved.

90F34774EEAD411DBC55EE9247A1D25A.description:
Solutions that use parallel computing can
scalemoreeffectivelythansolutionsthatuse
sequential computing.

686A092E3A734C5A89D6677E35B7B48F.description:
Parallel computing consists of a parallel portion
and a sequential portion.

B91C88F7CBDA42639B42CE308523D6B7.description:
Describebenefitsand
challenges of parallel and
distributed computing.

ECEB3425C6FE40849C65A80A8DA88EFF.description:
The “speedup” of a parallel solution is
measured in the time it took to complete the
task sequentially divided by the time it took to
complete the task when done in parallel.

241DF0B850D643558D4F1061DF541A77.description:
A parallel computing solution takes as long
as its sequential tasks plus the longest of its
parallel tasks.

8D66FE37E4BB45819E38AF65E1390B78.description:
A sequential solution takes as long as the sum
of all of its steps.

C7453AA8EFDC42288C5AA92207846FFD.description:
Comparingefficiencyofsolutionscanbedone
by comparing the time it takes them to perform
the same task.

55A10CF004CB4D7F83B02AEF916AAF30.description:
Distributed computing is a computational
model in which multiple devices are used to run
a program.

C0C52DA62DC642C1876CABB409883E3B.description:
Parallel computing is a computational model
where the program is broken into multiple
smaller sequential computing operations,
some of which are performed simultaneously.

09C93414A0D44E8CB629E1BA5BA78C5F.description:
Sequential computing is a computational
model in which operations are performed in
order one at a time.

F86CE7D57E6D4EE9ABA5101C0C99185E.description:
For sequential, parallel, and
distributed computing:
a. Compare problem
solutions. 1.D
b. Determinetheefficiencyof
solutions.

1F0396FA9BB94E8BAB7F96F26CF7A1DD.description:
Parallel and distributed computing leverage multiple computers to more quickly
solve complex problems or process large data sets.

9C333C60291247A08B177F5242F049A7.description:
The redundancy of routing options between
two points increases the reliability of the
Internet and helps it scale to more devices and
more people.

ABE835CD9FCF49AE8FA2E4FD3D08770A.description:
Redundancy within a system often requires
additional resources but can provide the
benefitoffaulttolerance

E8C6240C0AD04908AE21E1CF86B4982A.description:
When a system can support failures and still
continue to function, it is called fault-tolerant.
This is important because elements of complex
systems fail at unexpected times, often in
groups, and fault tolerance allows users to
continue to use the network.

AC67FE85580B45C38540F119DDBC44E4.description:
If a particular device or connection on the
Internet fails, subsequent data will be sent via a
differentroute,ifpossible.

102F1FADE5A34F0AB665F3D2819FF57E.description:
One way to accomplish network redundancy is
by having more than one path between any two
connected devices.

EC653F39CCA44CE595339666408D5A48.description:
Redundancy is the inclusion of extra
components that can be used to mitigate
failure of a system if other components fail.

5F027F51F0974E43AFF4B9F3206C9322.description:
The Internethasbeenengineeredtobefaulttolerant, with abstractions for routing and
transmitting data.

FDE2EF291D7E4A4083429365E65B13E3.description:
Forfault-tolerantsystems,
like the Internet:
a. Describethebenefitsof
fault tolerance. 1.D
b. Explain how a given system
isfault-tolerant. 5.A
c. Identify vulnerabilities to
failure in a system.

4E103547E8D14C4AB55BDE4AEB32A744.description: Computer systems and networks facilitate the transfer of data.

640238E59DA443C1A1018A4CF5A21759.description: The World Wide Web uses the Internet.

EA82AF65A7464D64ABB6E5EA800C2FD2.description:
HTTP is a protocol used by the World Wide
Web.

6A9DE71059FC4AE3BDB25E6F63597DE4.description:
The World Wide Web is a system of linked
pages,programs,andfiles.

20E84F5398BC4DF8B39922BA063D2E40.description:
Describethedifferences
between the Internet and the
World Wide Web.

43E3E9C1CE8840D5AB15CE802069213A.description:
IP, TCP, and UDP are common protocols used
on the Internet.

91C34B93905A45999FA696C3D46429D5.description:
Packets may arrive at the destination in order,
out of order, or not at all.

225A013E5D5842FAB68F055C80FC61A4.description:
Packets contain a chunk of data and metadata
used for routing the packet between the origin
and the destination on the Internet, as well as
for data reassembly.

F6619004569C48BB8BB94C2EFCAB58D6.description:
Information is passed through the Internet as
a data stream. Data streams contain chunks of
data, which are encapsulated in packets.

79F2A62B3C4C4FC2B80A45220AFEE6C5.description:
Explain how data are sent
through the Internet via
packets.

19A952A754F0428B983FA93DE5C1716C.description: The Internet was designed to be scalable.

24363B6B18E54E2D8DF5A55FFDC54C1D.description:
The scalability of a system is the capacity for
thesystemtochangeinsizeandscaletomeet
new demands.

7E51B904D7BF4A21B766613AB56C05F1.description:
Routing on the Internet is usually dynamic; it is
notspecifiedinadvance.

CDF29FE9B5204565A8B5A8BAE966ADCE.description:
The protocols used in the Internet are open,
which allows users to easily connect additional
computing devices to the Internet.

1651B23E5A5F41FE918C9755CB39B30B.description:
A protocolisanagreed-uponsetofrulesthat
specify the behavior of a system.

6120A0C13DEF466793F8B1EAFC1D803A.description:
Access to the Internet depends on the ability
to connect a computing device to an Internetconnected device.

9C10C622B18846DFBAC13D359278962C.description:
The Internet is a computer network
consisting of interconnected networks that
usestandardized,open(nonproprietary)
communication protocols.

875FFD6384C14477A5E2EE0F6A8BD551.description:
Bandwidth is usually measured in bits per
second.

6DEBE6D1733943BB9DC1BDACC5965B74.description:
The bandwidth of a computer network is the
maximum amount of data that can be sent in a
fixedamountoftime.

2FAF6EB127714524B08B3D3B756CA1EC.description:
A path between two computing devices on a
computer network (a sender and a receiver) is
a sequence of directly connected computing
devices that begins at the sender and ends at
the receiver.

E1DB9018D8494892AC1F41F36E12A694.description:
A computer network is a type of computing
system.

55307369044549B4B29848A54DA9C2A9.description:
A computer network is a group of
interconnected computing devices capable of
sending or receiving data.

95ACA6D264834AE9AA148FF23E4C8499.description:
A computing system is a group of computing
devices and programs working together for a
common purpose.

C30805671A5B46D9AED04380AD43F5A9.description:
A computing device is a physical artifact that
can run a program. Some examples include
computers, tablets, servers, routers, and smart
sensors.

5B5102CAE9B94DD288BAA7FB1F49DF22.description:
Explain how computing
devices work together in a
network.

2F039F752EF44A29A30C2E8D324A6392.description: Computer systems and networks facilitate the transfer of data.

072DB190B3374FCAB4FE9805D6731F62.description:
An undecidable problem may have some
instances that have an algorithmic solution, but
there is no algorithmic solution that could solve
all instances of the problem.

7087FC3910134E8CA7EB418735CE1F15.description:
An undecidable problem is one for which no
algorithm can be constructed that is always
capableofprovidingacorrectyes-or-no
answer.

E6CC03DD7FAA42F0A3665D541FC6B73A.description:
A decidable problem is a decision problem for
which an algorithm can be written to produce a
correct output for all inputs (e.g., “Is the number
even?”).

8000BF6BC4F6427C9DB58F5AD382418D.description:
Explain the existence of
undecidable problems in
computerscience.

33ACC7164D3F4A828E4B821E906EC39D.description:
There exist problems that computers cannot solve, and even when a computer can
solve a problem, it may not be able to do so in a reasonable amount of time.

7756247CCC64434EBD76C3865199E32D.description:
A heuristic is an approach to a problem that
produces a solution that is not guaranteed to
be optimal but may be used when techniques
thatareguaranteedtoalwaysfindanoptimal
solution are impractical.

691DBEAFCE7B4AA3852A18CC12A0E70C.description:
Some problems cannot be solved in a
reasonable amount of time because there is no
efficientalgorithmforsolvingthem.Inthese
cases, approximate solutions are sought.

CE399B0AE6E346D9978148A1E8974961.description:
Algorithmswithapolynomialefficiencyor
slower (constant, linear, square, cube, etc.)
are said to run in a reasonable amount of
time. Algorithms with exponential or factorial
efficienciesareexamplesofalgorithmsthatrun
in an unreasonable amount of time.

E0EE306AFDF44A5A88AA7491BE92FBB8.description:
Analgorithm’sefficiencycanbeinformally
measured by determining the number of times
a statement or group of statements executes.

7189396AC65D43D787A81663FAABAFEA.description:
Efficiency is an estimation of the amount of
computational resources used by an algorithm.
Efficiencyistypicallyexpressedasafunction
ofthesizeoftheinput.

A0946AA19019436996740DD2A00037F7.description:
A decision problem is a problem with a yes/no
answer (e.g., is there a path from A to B?). An
optimization problem is a problem with the goal
offindingthe“best”solutionamongmany(e.g.,
what is the shortest path from A to B?).

49A776D660E642DEA634E01F72E72405.description:
A problem is a general description of a task
that can (or cannot) be solved algorithmically.
An instanceofaproblemalsoincludesspecific
input. For example, sorting is a problem; sorting
the list (2,3,1,7) is an instance of the problem.

2745020798B34BF1A72A8695EA0DC28A.description:
For determining the
efficiencyofanalgorithm:
a. Explainthedifference
between algorithms that
run in reasonable time and
thosethatdonot.  1.D
b. Identify situations where a
heuristic solution may be
moreappropriate.

C075D0326FBD4B468D92C6B5290374C9.description:
There exist problems that computers cannot solve, and even when a computer can
solve a problem, it may not be able to do so in a reasonable amount of time.

03EC41AB81DD4481B14B8E86380B9D18.description:
Random number generators can be used to
